n, Anglie"},"da":{"–1252":"–1252","1179–Female":"1179–Afdød","1204–1252":"1204–1252","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Afdød","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","April 1230":"april 1230","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","Kelley, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"–1252":"–1252","1179–Female":"1179–Overleden","1204–1252":"1204–1252","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Overleden","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","April 1230":"april 1230","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","Kelley, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"–1252":"–1252","1179–Female":"1179–Deceased","1204–1252":"1204–1252","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","April 1230":"April 1230","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","Kelley, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kelly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Aileen, John Patrick, Siobhan, Liam, Brigid, Donovan, Eamon, Parnell, Aidan, Clancy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallaigh</b>, or, in some areas, <b>Mac Ceallaigh</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Ceallach</i>’, an ancient Irish personal name, originally a byname meaning ‘bright-headed’, later understood as ‘frequenting churches’ (Irish <i>ceall</i>). There are several early Irish saints who bore this name. <i>Kelly</i> is now the most common of all surnames in Ireland.","Scottish: habitational name from either the lands of Kelly, near Arbroath (Angus), Kellie in Carnbee (Fife), or Kelly in Methlick (Aberdeenshire). Each of these placenames is from Pictish <i>celli</i> or Gaelic <i>coille</i> ‘wood’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-in</i>. Alternatively, from the lands of Kelloe in the barony of Hume (Berwickshire), whose name is of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Kelley","meanings":["Irish (Offaly) and English: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kilkelly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Bridie.","Irish (Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Ceallaigh</b> ‘son of the devotee of (Saint) Ceallach’ (see   Kelly  )."]},{"name":"Killeen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donovan, Kieran, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cillín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cillín</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Ceallach</i> (see   Kelly  ). The name was borne by various early Irish saints, including the leader of a 7th-century mission to Franconia and Thuringia, hence the popularity of the personal name   Kilian   in medieval central Europe."]},{"name":"Kellis","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name. Compare   Kellison  .","Greek: descriptive nickname for a bald man, from <i>kelis</i> ‘bald’, a word of Turkish origin (from <i>kel</i> ‘bald’).","History: As a surname of Scottish origin, this has been established in NC since the 18th century."]},{"name":"Kellie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kellison","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":81,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":90,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William de Kelly was born in Devon, England as the son of Warren de Kelly and Mrs. Warren de Kelly. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William de Kelly. He died in 1252."},"et":{"–1252":"–1252","1179–Female":"1179–Surnud","1204–1252":"1204–1252","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","April 1230":"aprill 1230","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","Kelley, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"–1252":"–1252","1179–Female":"1179–Kuollut","1204–1252":"1204–1252","1175–1230":"117